Tuesday morning, 08:03. Waiting for the Northern line at Balham. 3 minutes to fill.

"Muesli. A delicious way to make sure today isn't one of those days". Right. Who knew a horrible breakfast cereal could have so much power? Maybe it just sets your expectations suitably low for the rest of the day. If you start off with disappointment, things can only go up from there.

"Become who you want to be. Get a place at Birkbeck". Good idea. Shame I don't know who I want to be.

"Meet someone amazing". Sounds lovely. You have to meet a lot of strange people first, by the sound of it. One day I'll have to sign up though. Can't carry on like this forever.

"Feeling unwell? Seek help at the next station. It's quicker to ask staff for help at a station than pull the passenger alarm between stops". Thanks, London Underground. Can your staff help me with this hangover?

The platform is filling up. 1 minute. On my left, behind the yellow line, a guy in dreadlocks reads today's Metro — some tediousness about a report into child obesity. On my right, a woman checks her makeup in the camera of her phone. To her right, a guy in a bowler hat. What is this, the 1960s? Hipster twat. Shit, eye contact! I flick my head forward. Feels like he's still looking.

At last. "The train now arriving is for all stations to Edgware via Bank".
> 1
I glance to my right. I can't see the hipster at all now.

The doors open. I get on.
hr { border: 0; height: 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3); margin-top: 16px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
Pretty full as usual. No expectation of a seat, so I barely look for one. Space over by the opposite door though.

No challenges here. I just glide to a pole and grab hold of it without a moment's thought. No decisions, no effort, no choice, no problem.

Auto-pilot. It's almost a reflex reaction to the sound of the alarm clock, to get up, leave the flat, and catch the tube to work. Ten stops to Bank, change to the Central line, one stop to Liverpool Street. Turn left, up the escalator, left, through the barriers, right, up the stairs. Up the ramp and past the huge big rusty metal sculpture. Through the revolving doors. Rummage in pockets for security badge, and into the office. All automatic, and I'll barely notice a thing.

"Morning, Zoran" the boss will say, and he'll hear a reply. But he only sees the body of Zoran Tharp, and my mind will be elsewhere.

The day will pass, eventually, and I'll go home and heat up that second pizza I bought yesterday, then go to bed having hardly troubled my synapses in 16 hours.

Possibly the most exciting thing I will do today is go for a shit. Sneak off from my desk for 10 minutes of unscheduled me-time. Like a mini holiday.

The doors open. One person gets on.

This station is Clapham South.
> 1
Beep-beep-beep-beep-beep.

The doors close. The train lurches onward.

Despite the clatter of the train, and the rocking motion, there is a peaceful stillness here. Many people in a small area, yet we are all alone. It is comfortable, in a strange way, even though I am standing up, having to hold on so I don't fall over the next time the train unexpectedly yanks left or right. Almost meditative. Almost soothing my hangover. Almost.

Like water droplets coming together and flowing through a pipe, the Tube carries us along, we are swept through from home to the office. It's automatic. Water starts at one place and ends up at the other, and so do we. We are packed together and become indistinguishable from a general flow.

This station is Clapham Common.
> 1
They'll have driverless trains down here eventually. In fact, the drivers are pretty much automatic already. One button to open the doors. One button to make the train go. That's all there is to it. I wonder what they think about up there. Their whole day just kind of happens for them. Not that different to mine really. An automatically guided train, taking automatically guided citizens to their workplaces, on schedule, like clockwork. Machines carrying machines. Is anybody conscious? Am I even really here?

This station is Clapham North.
> 1
Sometimes the machine breaks. A spring snaps, and the clockwork mechanism seizes up. But we are not cogs, are we? Supposedly we have free will. I have free will. I don't need to be part of this.

We have arrived at Stockwell.

Normally I would stay on the train. But there is a sign pointing to the Victoria line. Dare I?
> 1
Fair enough. Better be sensible. I don't want to get fired.

About 15 people get off the train. All the people standing between the seats took the free ones though, so there's still nowhere to sit. I'll carry on hanging here. At least it's not so packed, and I can breathe now.

This station is Oval. The doors open.

Well, even if I wanted to escape and do something different today, there's nowhere I can go — other than turn around and go south again. May as well stay on. The next station is Kennington — I could change there for the other branch of the Northern line.

All I can do is wait.
> 1
One woman rushes on as the doors close, and we're off again.

We come to a stop in the tunnel. Nobody says anything. Why would they? There are no thoughts to communicate at this moment in time. We know trains stop, and then they start. Barely worth noticing, let alone commenting on. Like so much in life. One minute later, on we go.

Here we are now at Kennington.

I could stay on the train again. Or I could change to the Charing Cross branch. I could do that. There is nothing stopping me.
> 1
Fine. I'll stay on for one more stop then.

Five people get off, and I could have had a seat if I was quick enough. One man in a suit gets on, and the doors close.

I'll just be a good boy and wait here, as the train takes me ever closer to yet another day, a day that will be almost exactly the same as yesterday.

We stop in the tunnel again. After a minute, the driver's voice breaks the silence. "Sorry for the short hold up, we're just held at a red signal, we'll be on the move shortly". Well, that's useful information. Of course we're stopped because we're held at a red signal. Why is there a red signal though? "Once again, apologies for the delay, we're just being held at a red signal. We'll be on the move again very soon. When we do, this train will be calling at all stations to High Barnet via Bank". This guy clearly just loves the sound of his own voice. Maybe he really wants to be a breakfast radio DJ.

Almost as soon as he stops speaking, we're on our way again, but mercifully he doesn't feel the need to come back and inform us all of this obvious fact.

We have arrived at Elephant and Castle. I can change to the Bakerloo line. I think I'd like that. I could also stay on the train again.
> 1
Good self control there. I suppose I should feel pleased with myself. I do not feel pleased with myself. I am denying my true self in favour of being a nice compliant automaton. This is not what I want. It's what you want.

Soon enough we're at Borough. I can't even make a choice here. All I can do is stay on the Northern line.
> 1
Nobody gets on at Borough. The doors close, then open, then close again.

Onwards we go, and nobody is looking very happy. Maybe some people describe the inside of the tube as being like a cattle truck, not because of the crowded conditions but because we're piled in anonymously and simply awaiting the fate of whatever the day brings. I'm starting to feel the cows have an easier time of it — at least they get a quick bolt through their head at the other end.

We are at London Bridge.

I could change to the Jubilee line.

I could do that. I should totally do that.

It's either that or stay here. With Daisy and Buttercup.
> 2
Is that it? Just stand here? Don't complain, know my place? Don't choose life — choose not to choose?

Why do you want me to do that? Who says you're in charge?

Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep-Beep
> 1
I jump out of the train as the door closes onto me. Its rubber edge barges heavily into my right shoulder and knocks me off balance. Fortunately I avoid being crushed against the inside of the doorway and I spin out onto the platform.

That's going to be a bruise.

This way to the Jubilee line.
> 1
I follow the signs to the Jubilee line. It's not a very quick interchange — down some corridors and up and down some steps. But it doesn't take a huge amount of effort, and here I am on the platform, going somewhere else.

That was pretty easy really.

A train pulls in and I can get on.
> 1
hr { border: 0; height: 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3); margin-top: 16px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
I can see a young guy, a male student, a middle-aged woman and a fat man.

The doors close.
> interact person23
He's wearing a T-shirt and picking his nose. Yuck. What can you do though? Ask him to stop? Is he going to eat that?
> eat
Eugh. What do you want me to do, go up and ask him if I can have some? You're not helping me feel any better.

Maybe I'll go to the park.
> interact person31
She reminds me of a teacher I used to have at school. A French teacher, whose name I can't quite remember. Scary lady. Always telling us off for not revising hard enough for her vocab tests. Maybe it is her. Hard to tell. It's been a long time. I'm still slightly scared of her even now, even though she has no power over me, and it might not even be her anyway. Still, best not to risk attracting her attention.

Hyde Park would be nice today.

This is Southwark.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> attention2
Why are you making me look? I think it is her. I think that's a mole on her right cheek —  it's got to be. I'm not going to say anything. She wouldn't remember me anyway. And besides, I've pretty much forgotten all the French I once knew, and I don't want to get a bollocking. Je voudrais to just stay here quietly, merci beaucoup.

Getting on are a man, a man in a suit and another man.

The doors close.

I can see a young guy, a male student, a middle-aged woman, a fat man, a man, a man in a suit and another man.
> interact person11
Unlike most people it seems, he's not filling his journey by looking at a newspaper or listening to earphones. He is muttering to himself a bit though, as he stares vacantly into space.
> muttering
Impossible to hear what he's saying. He doesn't seem threatening though, somehow. He seems too nerdy to be dangerous. I mean, he probably has a proper job and everything. Which is probably the perfect cover. He's probably exactly the kind of person that would have somebody kept in his basement.

This is Waterloo.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person3
He could not look more like a student. He's sat there with a pile of papers, looking through page after page of tables. The stripy jumper, brown trousers and brown shoes finish off the look. He is clearly very comfortable fitting into that category of person. He has fully bought in to that lifestyle and appearance. It makes me feel somewhat jealous actually —  I'd never want to look like that, but I'd love to be able to fit in, and know my place, and be happy with it. Maybe in blissful ignorance of other options, but blissful nonetheless.

This headache is creeping up on me. Coffee. Sweet coffee.

The middle-aged woman gets off the train.

The doors close.

I can see a young guy, a male student, a fat man, a man, a man in a suit and another man.
> interact person4
His belly hangs over his belt. Maybe if he just loosened his belt a bit, his weight wouldn't have been the first thing I noticed.
> interact person22
He has an earring, which I suppose makes him feel more individual than the rest of the people he works with. Yet he still adheres to a dress code. An act of futile rebellion.

This is Westminster.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person20
He is wearing a grey striped shirt, grey trousers and grey shoes. Even his hair is going grey. Mr. Monochrome.

Headache headache headache.

The fat man, the young guy and the man get off the train.
Getting on are a woman and an old woman.

The doors close.

I can see a male student, a man in a suit, a man, a woman and an old woman.
> interact person19
She is reading some kind of arty magazine.

We're now heading onto the "old" bit of the Jubilee line - it used to run from Charing Cross to Westminster and then up to Stanmore. You can't get to Charing Cross any more on the Jubilee, but the line from Green Park to there still exists, and they use the platforms at Charing Cross for filming sometimes.
> interact person7
She is sat in the priority seat. At least, I presume it's a she. There is a lot of wispy white hair around the chin area. I would think a man would keep his beard in better shape, and wear it with pride.

This is Green Park.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> wait2
I stand for a while staring at the tunnel wall flying by with all its pipes.

Maybe I'm too hung over to handle the park today. Maybe I'll just stay down here. It feels safer — no phone signal, so nobody from work can reach me. I could stay down here all day.

The man in the suit and the old woman get off the train.
Getting on are a man in sunglasses and a woman drinking coffee.

The doors close.

I can see a male student, a man, a woman, a man in sunglasses and a woman drinking coffee.
> interact person21
Her coffee cup has her name scrawled on it in black felt tip. Roberta. I know nothing about her, but now I know her name —  which is more than I can say for anybody else in this carriage. It's like we have some kind of connection now.
> roberta
I don't like her name. She looks like she's probably nice, but I think her name is horrible. It's kind of manly. Like Geraldine or Bernardette —  big blokey names with a small concession to femininity at the end. Makes me think of an old man with a big beard wearing a flowery dress.

This is Bond Street.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person25
Sunglasses, down here? And chewing gum, with his mouth wide open. All nonchalant and cool, like he doesn't need to be here, but hey, he just puts up with it, y'know, why complain? So many reasons to hate. He's really playing with that gum as well, like he's totally the boss of it. Everything's going his way —  apart from his debilitating eye disorder which means his retinas will fall out if he's exposed to more than two photons at a time. What a colossal prick.

The woman drinking coffee, the man in sunglasses and the male student get off the train.
Getting on are a man in a suit, a man in a jumper, a woman and a chubby couple.

The doors close.

I can see a man, a woman, a man in a suit, a man in a jumper, another woman and a chubby couple.
> interact person27
It's quite a big blue jumper —  inappopriately warm for both the weather and the temperature down here on the tube, I should think. And what's that suspicious white stain at the bottom? Does he realise that's there? I hope that's yogurt, or the milk from his breakfast cereal.

I'm sweating. This pain is like something tearing in the centre of my head.
> interact person6
They are dressed in matching waterproof jackets, and the guy is holding a tatty guide to London. I wonder where they're off to, what their holiday schedule has in store for today.

This is Baker Street.
There's no need for me to travel to the darkest reaches of the outer zones. Time for me to get off this train.
> unboard
hr { border: 0; height: 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3); margin-top: 16px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
I could change to the northbound Bakerloo line, the southbound Bakerloo line, the eastbound Hammersmith & City/Circle lines, the westbound Hammersmith & City, the eastbound Metropolitan line or the southbound Jubilee line.
> change southbound Bakerloo line
I follow the signs.

I am standing on the platform for the southbound Bakerloo line at Baker Street.

I could wait for a train here, or change to another line.
> next
A Bakerloo line train arrives. The doors open. I can get on.
> board
I get on the train.

I can see a man in a suit, a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a young pretty woman.

The doors close.
> interact person30
The woman is sat in a priority seat with the baby on her lap. The baby is looking at me.
> baby
The baby is staring at me as if he knows something terrible. As if he's accusing me of something. But I haven't done anything. Well, I'm skipping work. But how does the baby know that? He looks like he would tell everybody everything, if only he had the power of language. That's where I win, mate. All you can do is keep staring.

I can't see properly. My head is pounding.

I think I can smell cigarette smoke.

My fellow passengers have become murky. I can barely see them — just blurry, shadowy outlines.

The sound of tinny headphones has disappeared.

A silhouette with a hat walks past me.

Breathe, relax. It will pass.

I close my eyes.

I slowly open them again.
> 1
The tinny headphones are back. I can't smell cigarette smoke any more.

I can see a man in a suit, a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a young pretty woman.
> stare
OK, I'd prefer it if he stopped staring to be honest. That's the trouble with babies. No concept of social norms. They don't know that you shouldn't keep staring at people.

This is Regent's Park.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person5
She is incredibly pretty in that fragile sort of way. A fine bone structure, I suppose, that looks like it might break at any moment.

Nobody gets on or off. The doors close.

I can see a man in a suit, a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a young pretty woman.
> bone
Truly an exquisite skeleton. Even her X-rays would have me sighing wistfully. And she knows it.
> interact person18
He is a builder by the looks of it —  paint-splattered jeans. He is sleeping next to another builder who looks almost the same. These two big burly men look almost cute, blissfully asleep like enormous babies.

This is Oxford Circus.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person13
He listens diligently to his iPod through white earbuds. I can't hear what he's listening to —  which is unusual for those stock earbuds. He seems to be listening very carefully though. He has glossy black shoes with bright red laces. The only dash of colour on him. Like a little private joke.

The man in the suit and the young pretty woman get off the train.
Getting on is a large man.

The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a large man.
> interact person14
He is wearing a leather jacket, a woolly hat, and, bizarrely, shorts. He also has a massive
				beard —  the top half of him must be a lot warmer than the bottom half.
> wait2
I look at the floor, hiding its dirt with its colourful speckles. Clever floor. Also, kind of disgusting.

This is Piccadilly Circus.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> wait2
Time continues to elapse.

The large man gets off the train.
Getting on is a man.

The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a man.
> interact person26
He's eating a steaming hot tub of porridge. It's pretty hot down here already —  surely the last thing anybody needs is piping hot breakfast mush?

My eyes are going again. Blurriness. And my head. Thump. Thump. Thump.

That smell of cigarette smoke again. Who is that?

I'm trying to see.
> 1
Slowly I regain focus. There he is, on my left, puffing away. Who the fuck does he think he is?

But wait, smoke coming from my right too. Somebody else, facing the other way — another guy wearing a fucking bowler hat. When did this become a thing?

And nobody seems bothered in the slightest. Well, I'm certainly not going to be the one to say anything.

Just look away.
> 2
The smoke makes my eyes water. Above the first smoker's head there's an advert which I can't quite read.

"The world's most popular cassette deck". That's what it looks like it says.

I close my eyes. The smell fades.

I open my eyes again.
> 3
Things seem sharper once more. The cigarettes have disappeared, and so has the smell.

Ah, it's not the world's most popular cassette deck. It's the world's most advanced nutrition supplements for pregnant women. I wonder how I got that muddled up.

Where did bowler hat guy go? Weird.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a man.
> wait2
I stand for a while staring at the tunnel wall flying by with all its pipes.

Why would a hangover make me think I was surrounded by people smoking? That is fucked up. I don't want to think about it. If I don't think about it, maybe I can forget it happened.

This is Charing Cross.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> wait2
I look at the floor, still cleverly hiding its dirt there.

That must have been normal, once, sparking up on the tube. Puffing away out of habit. An unremarkable default setting. Yet fatal. The cool kids at school all smoked. Popular people lulling others into their deadly trap. All in the name of fitting in. Easier to copy than to think for yourself. I wonder if we're really any more grown up now? None of us in this carriage are smoking, but what other long term traps have we blundered into without thinking?

The man gets off the train.
Getting on are a woman and child.

The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby and a woman and child.
> interact person2
Like all children, the boy completely fails to be able to sit still for any length of time. His mother sits next to him, not paying much attention.
> attention
The child starts pulling faces at the other passengers. What a quandry. This child knows none of the rules. Are we supposed to smile back? Look annoyed? Just ignore him?

This is Embankment.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> wait2
Time continues to elapse.

Getting on are a smiling woman and a trendy guy.

The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby, a woman and child, a smiling woman and a trendy guy.
> interact person12
She is smiling, then suppressing it. But she's not doing very well at suppressing it. I wonder what she's seen. I hope it's not me. My cock's not hanging out, is it?

The train slows down suddenly, then speeds up, then slows down suddenly again. Must be the emergency brake.

The drivers voice crackles over the speakers. "Please do not lean against the doors, stand away from the doors please."
> hanging
Of course it's not.

Anyway, if my cock was hanging out, she'd simply faint, right... right? Or pull the alarm lever. Or actually, do absolutely nothing at all. I could get my cock out now. What would happen? What would really happen?

This is Waterloo.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> cock
I'm not getting my fucking cock out. What is wrong with you?

The woman and child, the smiling woman and the trendy guy get off the train.
Getting on are a man with a moustache, a teenage girl and a man.

The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby, a man with a moustache, a teenage girl and a man.
> interact person24
Apart from a huge bushy moustache, he is clean shaven. He looks a bit like Lord Kitchener in those posters from the First World War. He might turn round at any second, point at me and say "I want YOU".

The train slows down suddenly again, and speeds up and slows down once more. This merry dance.

"Once again, do not lean against the doors, stand away from the doors. If you keep leaning against the doors, this train will be taken out of service."
> you
It would be nice to feel wanted, but not by somebody who just wants to send me to a pointless death in a muddy hole in France.

This is Lambeth North.
I could get off here. Or wait.
> interact person16
She is wearing huge bright green headphones on top of her long black hair. She gets her
				phone out to check her reflection in the camera. That's the second person I've seen doing that this morning. I remember when people used to use mirrors. Using your phone to see what you look like seems like a waste —  such an enormous amount of technology for such a very small problem.

Nobody gets on or off. The doors close.

I can see a sleeping man, a woman with a baby, a man with a moustache, a teenage girl and a man.
> interact person17
He is balding, wearing jeans and tatty Converse trainers, and doing something on a Macbook Air. He has a bag stuffed with papers and files.

Great, once again we're stopping and starting. I can't see anybody on this carriage leaning against the doors though.
> wait2
I stand for a while staring at the tunnel wall flying by with all its pipes.

This is Elephant & Castle.

The driver's voice booms out. "Apologies ladies and gentlemen, due to a fault with the doors, this train is now being taken out of service. Your next service is about one minute behind this one. All change please, all change. Once again, due to a fault with the doors this train is not in service. All change please."

Well, all I can do is get off.
> unboard
hr { border: 0; height: 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3); margin-top: 16px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
I could change to the northbound Bakerloo line, the northbound Northern line or the southbound Northern line.
> change northbound Northern line
I follow the signs.

I am standing on the platform for the northbound Northern line at Elephant & Castle.

I could wait for a train here, or change to another line.
> next
A Northern line train arrives. The doors open. I can get on.
> board
I get on the train.

She is right there in front of me.

Heather.
> 1
Heather. Heather. Heather. Butterflies. Don't throw up.

It's been four months. She's probably forgotten me. I should have called. At least sent her an email. Or added her on Facebook. I was too scared. Anyway, I didn't have any contact details. Or even a surname. Should've asked Dave. But I didn't want to be too eager. I played it cool. I probably played it too cool. And now I'm starting from absolute zero.

Her hair is different. I liked it before. Now it's even better.

Her eyes. Captivating. They have swallowed me. I am powerless. I am unable to look anywhere else.

I must have already massively overstepped the unwritten rules about eye contact.

Can't back out now. Even if she doesn't remember me, she can't have failed to spot the man who has just been staring at her for too long already. How long has it been? It feels like forever. It can only have been a few seconds — the doors are still open.

Must say something.

Must be funny. Friendly. Charming. Not scary. Not creepy. Maybe I should apologise for staring. Don't want to apologise for staring — I want to look at her forever. Must think quickly. Must speak soon. Already left it a bit too long. Too much pressure. Must say something. Anything.

"Hello"
> 1
Well, that word squeaked out like a rat's fart. I've fucked it up already.

But then a smile bursts across her face, and her eyes sparkle, as if she has suddenly been reactivated.

"Hi!..."

She points at me and pauses, loading data from memory banks. Two seconds later — "Zoran! Dave's friend, isn't it? How are you doing?"

I have been obsessing over you every night for months, even though there was a good chance I would never see you again.

"Fine. Good, actually. How's things with you?"
> 1
"Good."

Smile. Eye contact. Silence. Fuck!

Quick, what did we talk about at Dave's party? Her job... er, some kind of Social Media Somebody.

"How's the world of social media then?"
> 1
"Oh, fine."

What? Is that it? OK, next item. Why is she making this difficult?

For someone who is apparently a professional people person, she's really bad at holding a conversation.

Is this some deliberate game? Let's play it then. Eye contact and silence. How long can we keep this up?

One, two, three, four, five.
> 1
Damn you!

"So, er..."
> 1
Think, think. God, this was a lot easier after mojitos.

We talked for such a long time before, like it could never end. We got on the tube then, too — I was heading back to my place, she to hers — and we talked about the Underground most of the way. We talked about tube mice, abandoned stations, all that history, and just what is behind those doors you see on some platforms that just say "PRIVATE ROD"?

Right, so social media is a dead end. Was she going anywhere on holiday?

What am I, a fucking hairdresser? There's got to be something more interesting than that.

"How was Morocco?"
> 1
"Oh, we haven't been yet, that's next month."

Great. Serves me right for asking a boring question. And "we"? There was never a "we", was there? She was going on her own, wasn't she?

The cat! She had just got a cat! Thank fuck.

"How's the cat doing?"
> 1
"Settling in. Behaving herself. Had to take her to the vet last week."

"Yeah?"

"She wasn't eating much. Doesn't seem to be anything wrong with her though."

OK, so it turns out I'm not the slightest bit interested in the cat. How is this so different to before, when conversation flowed so freely? Like we had always known each other somehow, and had just been reunited. We were about to start something big, something life-changing. There was a connection there. So much excitement, so many possibilites. That fire still burns within me. Did she just move on? Is she just really... nice?

That's it, isn't it? Social Media job — completely worthless in the real world, but it's the kind of role they would give to someone who possessed no real skills other than being fucking lovely, just so they could get to hang around with her all the time.

No. No. Wait. No need for pointless anger. Maybe she's just nervous too.

"Where are you off to then?"
> 1
"Just on my way to work. What about you?"

Ah. yes. What am I doing here? Playing truant, like a schoolboy? Not exactly sexy, is it?

"Are you alright? You've gone very pale."

I'm fine. I'm fine. My left arm has gone numb, but I'm fine. Slightly dizzy. Just need to breathe. More oxygen. Am I having a heart attack? Both arms numb now. My fingers tingle.

"I'm fine."
