I am cold.

Silence. Blackness.

A cold, claggy sensation. Tastes like clay.
> 1
It is clay. Filling my mouth, my nose and throat. I am suspended in cold clay.

I can't move.

But I don't mind.

I can't breathe. But I don't mind that either.

I feel very peaceful here. A sense of belonging.
> 1
My arms are clay. My legs are clay.

I feel, for the first time in my life, that I fit in. I am part of one homogenous mass, and I have no urge to fight. I could stay here forever, cold and unchanging, unnoticed by anybody, underneath London, supporting London, built on clay, with bricks of clay.

Soon my head will be clay.

A small vibration.
> 1
Vibrations disturb the peace. A thudding murmur is being carried through the wet clay.

The vibrations increase. Noise, churning, scraping, slicing. Something is coming.
> 1
Light and air. I cough violently to clear my lungs, but there is nothing inside them. I breathe.

I am inside the tube carriage again.

Things are coming into focus. I thought I saw another bowler hat out of the corner of my eye. But there was nobody there.

I can see two female friends, a trendy guy, a man, a scruffy man and a young woman.

This is King's Cross St. Pancras.
I could get off here. Or wait.
