Time continues to elapse.

Just a dream. It must just have been a dream. A vivid, clay-filled dream.

The trendy guy gets off the train.
Getting on are a man and a small woman.

The doors close.

I can see two female friends, a man, a scruffy man, a young woman, another man and a small woman.
> interact person1
He is reading a biography of Kurt Cobain. The face on the cover is almost life size. If the man holds the book up in the right place, it will be like he lives among us again, albeit with the fixed expression of permanent self-satisfaction that the photo on the book's cover gives him.

I don't want to be clay. Is that unusual? Nobody says they want to be clay. But we all want to feel like we belong to something. To fit in easily, not to stand out. Not to fight. To give in. So simple, so comfortable.

 And suffocating.
> satisfaction
Although to be fair, if Kurt Cobain was riding in plain sight, on the tube, having faked his own death and then not noticably aged in any way, he'd have every right to look pleased with himself.

This is Euston.
There's no need for me to travel to the darkest reaches of the outer zones. Time for me to get off this train.
