This is Victoria.

The doors open. And there she is, standing on the platform.

Heather.

Eye contact.

Blank expression. Smile? I'm smiling. Nothing. Like she's not really there.

Doors bleeping. She's not even getting on then? I jump out as they snap shut behind me. Why stand on a platform if you're not getting on a train?

Now I'm standing on the platform in the same spot she was. But I can't see her now. Where has she gone?

A glimpse to my left. There she is, calmly walking up the platform.

I run.
> 1
She opens a cupboard and steps inside, closing the door behind her.

There is a sign on the door. It says "PRIVATE ROD".

I knock.
> 1
The door nudges open as I knock. Inside, a bank of flickering monitors. Sitting in front of them, facing away from me, a man.
> monitors
The monitors show CCTV images — some inside tube trains, some platforms. Most are in black and white, but a few are in colour.
> man
Illuminated only by the monitors in front of him, a man in a bowler hat.

I suppose should say "Hello".
> 1
"Come in, Zoran. Please close the door behind you."
> 1
There is a big rack of hard disks connected to the monitors. On one of the screens I think I spot a quick flash of my face. Looking closer, things seem familiar. There's a view inside a train carriage. I can see myself standing there. I'm looking at the two women who were having that inane conversation. Another monitor shows me looking at the chap with the Lord Kitchener moustache. And there's a monitor that shows me sitting opposite the young guy who was picking his nose.

On another monitor, I can see myself standing on a platform. I am waiting for the southbound Victoria line at Euston.

And what's that? On another monitor, a carriage full of people smoking. There's me, blinking, looking annoyed.

"Thanks for coming, Zoran". He pauses for a moment. "You've made good progress today."

"What?"
> 1
"Yes, well, aside from that". He scribbles down some notes on a pad of paper. "You should probably stop doing that."

"Stop doing what?"
> 1
"That - you just did it again. Well, it's up to you."

He turns back to face the monitors, and presses keys on a keyboard.

"That's right, I've turned back to face the monitors, and now I'm pressing keys on a keyboard. I can hear it when you do that too. You don't need to keep telling them this stuff. It's none of their business. You don't even know who they are."

The monitors flash up some more images from this morning. There's the muttering man.  And there's the man who was chuckling at platelet function disorders.

"They've been useful, Zoran, but I think you're done with them now. I've seen that you can make decisions for yourself. It was your decision that you made at London Bridge this morning. That decision to go your own way. I saw it, and you've got the bruise to prove it. They didn't want you to take that decision. They were going to let you go straight to work. You stopped that, Zoran. That was you. You did it. And you saw what happened next."

He writes something down on a form, and ticks a few boxes.

"There's a whole world out there, Zoran. And you can do anything. You know that now. You don't need help, or permission, to explore it and see what's out there."

And what about Heather?
> 1
He sucks air through his teeth. "Aaah. Well, that's awkward. You see, she's not here is she?"

It's pretty dark in this cupboard, but there's definitely no sign of her. But I definitely followed her in.

"Yes, you did follow her in. Well, that wasn't, how do we say this, that wasn't, er, real. I don't know — the real one — well, you bumped into the real one earlier, and if you ask me, well. Um."

He looks around awkwardly.

"Ok, maybe it was unfair of me to lure you in here using that image. Sorry. I don't know where she went when you blacked out. I didn't see. But I don't think it matters. You know, you can see, you saw... there was nothing there. Just empty hope."

He ticks another couple of boxes on his form, signs it, and places it on a pile.

"Don't hope, Zoran. Don't cross your fingers. Don't wait. Just get out there, assess your opportunities, take action. Nothing is going to happen, unless you make it happen."

He presses some more buttons, and the monitors switch off one by one.

"Good meeting you, Zoran," he says, tipping his hat. "I've got to get things set up for the next patient, I'm afraid. Take care of yourself, and hopefully... we'll never meet again."

I leave the dark cupboard. A train has just pulled in to the platform.
> 1
